<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 17. Final Stages of Assembling the Skirt.</h1>
<p><strong>I start joining the stiff inner construction with the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>First of all, I carefully align the princess seams of the skirt and the petticoat along the top edge. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then I attach the princess seams of the skirt to the princess seams of the petticoat with thread chains at about their mid-length. </strong>I am talking about the front princess seams and the side seams. My thread chains are about 2cm long for the mock-up, and they will be about 3-4cm long for the full-size skirt. In other words, I pull the princess seam of the skirt to the petticoat at its mid-length but leave some degree of looseness.</p>
<p><strong>I use the same kind of thread chains to connect the princess seams of the skirt with the princess seams of the petticoat at the bottom of the petticoat. </strong></p>
<p><strong>In order to do this, I find the bottom point of the corresponding princess seam of the petticoat. </strong>Please note that I start connecting the princess seams of the skirt with those of the petticoat from their mid-level while I can still lift up the skirt to reach the petticoat.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I bring the sewing needle in the seam allowance of the skirt princess seam at the determined level, make a strengthening stitch, and sew a thread chain.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>After sewing a thread chain, I need to attach it to the bottom of the princess seam of the petticoat. </strong>I bring the needle in the petticoat and all the way through the mesh fabric, pull in the slack, and secure the chain. Let me highlight it again that there should be enough free space between the joined skirt and petticoat. And please do this work with great attention: the chain may tear or come undone if it is not robust enough.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I move to the train after securing all gores with thread chains. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We want </strong>the train to drag along the floor in a beautiful way and move in sync with the skirt when the bride walks, and we also want it to look graceful when she is walking upstairs.</p>
<p><strong>I put the skirt with the petticoat on a stand to imitate walking upstairs. The bottom corner of the train overlays the train support very well. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I need to find a point along the central back seam of the train which would correspond with the bottom point of the train support. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>There is about 5-6cm between the bottom point of the support and the bottom point of the train. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I bring the needle in the found point along the central back seam of the train, make a strengthening stitch, and start sewing a thread chain. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The length of the thread chain corresponds with the distance between the bottom point of the train support when the bride is walking upstairs and the same point when she is walking over a horizontal surface. </strong></p>
<p><strong>In order to find it, I put the skirt on a horizontal surface, find the bottom point of the train support, and check whether the thread chain is long enough. </strong>I add 1cm extra just in case.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then I sew the thread chain to the bottom corner of the train support. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The face of the train is now firmly attached to the support. </strong>Of course, it is all done rather schematically on the mock-up, but you should secure it very well on the actual garment to be sure it doesn’t tear off, for example, if someone steps on the skirt by accident.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The train moves in sync with the skirt when attached to the support. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image052.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Once you are sure everything holds well, you can finish the waist area by hand or by machine depending on what the top of your garment will be like: dress, corset, bodice, etc. </strong>Then you should spread out the folds of the peplum to improve their shape and finish decorating the peplum and the joint between the skirt and the top part of the garment.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image054.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Pictures of the Finished Skirt.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image056.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image058.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%2017.files/image060.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
